	<p>
	<h4>functional programming</h4><p>
	<!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><!WA11><A HREF="ftp://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/emery/fp+oop=haskell.ps.gz"><B>FP+OOP=Haskell</B></a>, <!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><!WA12><a href="http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/emery">Emery Berger</a> (UT&nbsp;TR 92-30).<p> 

<font face="arial, helvetica">
<B>Abstract:</B> The programming language <!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><!WA13><A HREF="ftp://ftp.dcs.glasgow.ac.uk/pub/glasgow-fp/glasgow-fp.html">Haskell</A> adds object-oriented functionality (using a concept known as <em>type classes</em>) to a pure functional programming framework. This paper describes these extensions and analyzes its accomplishments as well as some problems.<P>

<!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><!WA14><A HREF="ftp://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/emery/fp+oop=haskell.dvi">dvi</A>, <!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><!WA15><A HREF="ftp://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/emery/fp+oop=haskell.ps.gz">
compressed PostScript</A>, or <!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><!WA16><A HREF="http://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/emery/fp+oop=haskell/fp+oop=haskell.html">HTML</A>.<p>
</font>

